8. ree adical cavengers
eleterious free radical byproducts, generated from oxyhemoglobin metabolism, have been implicated in the pathogenesis of cerebral vasospasm. etailed mechanisms have not yet been fully established. irilazad is a 21-aminosteroid that inhibits lipid peroxidation and scavenges free radicals.  large, international, randomized trial enrolled 1015 patients and demonstrated reduced mortality ( = 0.01) and improved 3-month clinical outcomes ( = 0.01) in patients receiving tirilazad when compared to those receiving placebo treatment. urther, the authors observed a nonsignificant reduction in symptomatic vasospasm, with increased benefit in males compared to females [63]. onversely, a similar orth merican trial randomized 897 patients to receive low-dose tirilazad, high-dose tirilazad, or placebo treatment and found no difference in symptomatic vasospasm incidence or 3-month outcomes [64].
anzino et al. hypothesized that, due to gender-related pharmacokinetics, benefits might be more apparent in women with administration of larger doses. his led to an international multicenter trial enrolling 819 women randomized to high-dose tirilazad or placebo treatment. atients who received tirilazad demonstrated reduced symptomatic vasospasm (33.7% versus 24.8%,  = 0.005) and decreased infarcts (8% versus 13%,  < 0.04) when compared to those receiving placebo. o significant difference in 3-month mortality rate was noted [65].  similar orth merican study enrolled 823 women and found no significant differences in symptomatic vasospasm or clinical outcome between patients who received tirilazad and those who received placebo. enefit was only noted in a subset of patients presenting with  grades  and   who demonstrated reduced mortality rates relative to placebo-treated patients ( = 0.016) [66].  recent meta-analysis, that included 3821 patients, found that individuals who received tirilazad demonstrated reduction in symptomatic vasospasm ( 0.80,  0.69 to 0.93) but no reduction in unfavorable clinical outcomes or mortality [67].
icaraven is a hydroxyl radical scavenger that was evaluated in a prospective randomized trial of 162 patients. n comparison to patients receiving placebo, those randomized to receive intravenous nicaraven demonstrated significant reductions in the incidence of delayed ischemic neurological deficits ( < 0.05), poor one-month outcomes ( < 0.05), and overall mortality ( < 0.05) [68]. bselen is a seleno-organic compound with antioxidant activity via a glutathione peroxidase-like mechanism. aito et al. failed to observe a significant reduction in vasospasm-related neurological deficits in 52 patients who were randomized to receive oral ebselen compared to those who received placebo treatment. owever, clinical outcomes were significantly improved ( = 0.005) and a corresponding decrease in both the incidence and extent of radiographic infarcts ( = 0.032) was noted [69]. ore recently, a new free radical scavenger, edaravone, was assessed in a randomized study. esults suggested a nonsignificant reduction in vasospasm-related deficits. urther, the authors noted a significant reduction in the incidences of vasospasm-induced cerebral infarction (0% versus 66%,  = 0.028) and poor 3-month outcome scores (0% versus 71%,  = 0.046) in the edaravone cohort when compared to those in the placebo group [70].8. Free Radical Scavengers
Deleterious free radical byproducts, generated from oxyhemoglobin metabolism, have been implicated in the pathogenesis of cerebral vasospasm. Detailed mechanisms have not yet been fully established. Tirilazad is a 21-aminosteroid that inhibits lipid peroxidation and scavenges free radicals. A large, international, randomized trial enrolled 1015 patients and demonstrated reduced mortality (P = 0.01) and improved 3-month clinical outcomes (P = 0.01) in patients receiving tirilazad when compared to those receiving placebo treatment. Further, the authors observed a nonsignificant reduction in symptomatic vasospasm, with increased benefit in males compared to females [63]. Conversely, a similar North American trial randomized 897 patients to receive low-dose tirilazad, high-dose tirilazad, or placebo treatment and found no difference in symptomatic vasospasm incidence or 3-month outcomes [64].
Lanzino et al. hypothesized that, due to gender-related pharmacokinetics, benefits might be more apparent in women with administration of larger doses. This led to an international multicenter trial enrolling 819 women randomized to high-dose tirilazad or placebo treatment. Patients who received tirilazad demonstrated reduced symptomatic vasospasm (33.7% versus 24.8%, P = 0.005) and decreased infarcts (8% versus 13%, P < 0.04) when compared to those receiving placebo. No significant difference in 3-month mortality rate was noted [65]. A similar North American study enrolled 823 women and found no significant differences in symptomatic vasospasm or clinical outcome between patients who received tirilazad and those who received placebo. Benefit was only noted in a subset of patients presenting with WFNS grades IV and V SAH who demonstrated reduced mortality rates relative to placebo-treated patients (P = 0.016) [66]. A recent meta-analysis, that included 3821 patients, found that individuals who received tirilazad demonstrated reduction in symptomatic vasospasm (OR 0.80, CI 0.69 to 0.93) but no reduction in unfavorable clinical outcomes or mortality [67].
Nicaraven is a hydroxyl radical scavenger that was evaluated in a prospective randomized trial of 162 patients. In comparison to patients receiving placebo, those randomized to receive intravenous nicaraven demonstrated significant reductions in the incidence of delayed ischemic neurological deficits (P < 0.05), poor one-month outcomes (P < 0.05), and overall mortality (P < 0.05) [68]. Ebselen is a seleno-organic compound with antioxidant activity via a glutathione peroxidase-like mechanism. Saito et al. failed to observe a significant reduction in vasospasm-related neurological deficits in 52 patients who were randomized to receive oral ebselen compared to those who received placebo treatment. However, clinical outcomes were significantly improved (P = 0.005) and a corresponding decrease in both the incidence and extent of radiographic infarcts (P = 0.032) was noted [69]. More recently, a new free radical scavenger, edaravone, was assessed in a randomized study. Results suggested a nonsignificant reduction in vasospasm-related deficits. Further, the authors noted a significant reduction in the incidences of vasospasm-induced cerebral infarction (0% versus 66%, P = 0.028) and poor 3-month outcome scores (0% versus 71%, P = 0.046) in the edaravone cohort when compared to those in the placebo group [70].
