<sections.8>
9. hromboxane nhibitors
he inhibition of platelet-derived thromboxane 2, which possesses regional vasoconstrictive and prothrombotic effects, has been investigated as a therapy for cerebral vasospasm.  1989 study observed significant reductions in vasospasm incidence and radiographic infarcts among patients randomized to receive ozagrel (-046), a selective thromboxane synthetase inhibitor [71]. dditional studies have been limited, principally, to apanese centers. ome apanese facilities have incorporated the treatment as standard therapy. he most recent publication, in 2008, compared 1138 patients who received ozagrel in combination with fasudil to 3690 patients treated with fasudil alone. linical outcomes were found to be similar. nterestingly, patients who received fasudil alone demonstrated a decreased incidence of radiographic infarcts (27.3% versus 32.4%,  < 0.01) and reduced symptomatic vasospasm rates (25.7% versus 32.0%,  < 0.01) compared to those on combination therapy. nterpretation of the results requires caution, as this investigation was a postmarketing surveillance study for fasudil and was not randomized [72].9. Thromboxane Inhibitors
The inhibition of platelet-derived thromboxane A2, which possesses regional vasoconstrictive and prothrombotic effects, has been investigated as a therapy for cerebral vasospasm. A 1989 study observed significant reductions in vasospasm incidence and radiographic infarcts among patients randomized to receive ozagrel (OKY-046), a selective thromboxane synthetase inhibitor [71]. Additional studies have been limited, principally, to Japanese centers. Some Japanese facilities have incorporated the treatment as standard therapy. The most recent publication, in 2008, compared 1138 patients who received ozagrel in combination with fasudil to 3690 patients treated with fasudil alone. Clinical outcomes were found to be similar. Interestingly, patients who received fasudil alone demonstrated a decreased incidence of radiographic infarcts (27.3% versus 32.4%, P < 0.01) and reduced symptomatic vasospasm rates (25.7% versus 32.0%, P < 0.01) compared to those on combination therapy. Interpretation of the results requires caution, as this investigation was a postmarketing surveillance study for fasudil and was not randomized [72].
